## 2. Part I ‚Äî the attack: workloads vs the champion's gates

Every workload is a schedule I re-walked against the champion's mechanisms
as written. "BREAKS" = the gate as stated is violated or unprovable;
"HOLDS" = survives with the stated bound.

### W1 ‚Äî O12 value-blind fan-out (vs G-N)

`c = a*0 + b`; 10k watchers on `c`; one deferred batch k held open across
frames; 100 `a.set(random)` per frame (all value-suppressed at `c`).

Champion walk: write 1 walks a‚Üíc, iterates 10k watchers, 10k setStates
(value-blind), 10k spurious renders in k's lane. Writes 2‚Äì100: dedup bits
set ‚Üí 10k bit loads per write = **1M loads/frame** (~0.5‚Äì1 ms). Render
re-arms ‚Üí next frame repeats: **10k spurious renders per frame, forever**.

- G-N as stated ("‚â§1 spurious render per (watcher, batch)") ‚Äî **BREAKS**:
  the bound is per render *cycle*, and a held batch has unboundedly many
  cycles. 10k renders/frame ‚âà 50‚Äì100 ms/frame of pure waste. The champion
  itself deferred this to SPK-N1; the adversarial grid row above needs no
  measurement to show the *stated* bound is wrong ‚Äî the knob cannot stay
  optional.
- Secondary: the 1M dedup loads/frame are real even when renders are
  deduped.

**Verdict: the evaluate-cutoff fallback must ship default-on at fan-out,
and repeat-walk cost needs structural pruning.** But the naive cutoff is
UNSOUND (I13-class): with `c = a && b`, t1 writes `a` (t1-world value of c
unchanged ‚Üí suppress), t2 writes `b` (t2-world unchanged ‚Üí suppress), the
joint {t1,t2} pass renders c=true with no pending update ‚Äî torn commit. A
retirement extends every world the same way (walked in ¬ß9.3). So the
hardened cutoff (¬ß9.3) is per-write equality **plus revocation** on
cone-sharing walks, propagation, and relevant retirements. Designed in
full below; SPK-N1's grid now *tunes the threshold*, it no longer decides
soundness.

### W2 ‚Äî O11 mount-fixup over-render (vs G-F and P1)

10 live held transitions (each wrote *something*, so every slot clock ‚âÝ 0);
mount a 1000-row list whose row nodes sit under one atom touched by ONE
transition (t3). Champion ¬ß10.2: every flagged mount schedules correctives
into **every** live deferred token ‚Üí 10 √ó 1000 = 10,000 lane-scheduled
updates, 10 full transition re-render passes over fresh rows at mount time.
P1's 10k-subscription-mount ‚â§15% budget is gone many times over; G-F's
"‚â§ live-deferred-count per mount" bound is *met* and still catastrophic ‚Äî
**the gate's bound is the problem** (10√ó over-render is inside the gate).

**Verdict: BREAKS (gate mis-specified).** Repair: the fixup consults
`touchedSlots(n) ‚à© liveDeferred` ‚Äî rows touched only by t3 get exactly one
corrective, in t3's lane, joining t3's already-pending render. Soundness
needs the propagation invariant (a fresh mount's first evaluation adds
edges; edge-add propagation marks the node before the layout fixup runs) ‚Äî
¬ß10.2 carries the induction. The I18 hole (live-token enumeration goes
empty when a batch retires inside the mount window) is repaired in the same
function by an unconditional committed-world version compare.

### W3 ‚Äî held-open transition read bursts (vs G-E/¬ß13.3)

Transition k held open 10 s over a 1000-row deferred list; user types: each
keystroke is an urgent batch that writes an atom **disjoint** from k's
cone, renders, commits (= retires), and interrupts k, which restarts.

Champion: (a) memo keys are `(node, worldKey)` with the **pin in the key**;
every k-pass restart captures a new pin ‚Üí new worldKey ‚Üí 100% memo miss
across passes of the *same* transition. (b) Worse, ¬ß4.3 step 2 bumps
`worldMemoEpoch` at **every** retirement ‚Äî each keystroke's commit nukes
every world memo in the system. Net: every keystroke re-evaluates k's
entire visible flagged region (1000 rows √ó their computed chains), ~10√ó/s.
The ladder cannot save it: the ladder lives on memos, and the memos are
gone. G-E's "world-eval cost ‚àù flagged/non-fresh region" is technically
satisfied **per pass** ‚Äî the gate failed to say "amortized across passes",
so the cliff hides inside it.

**Verdict: BREAKS (two compounding design choices, one mis-scoped gate).**
Repair (¬ß8): pinless memo keys + pin-window lemma; retirement relevance
ring instead of the epoch nuke; per-(atom, maskId) fold caches. After
repair the keystroke costs 1000 ring/clock checks (~¬µs), zero re-folds for
disjoint writes. SPK-G8 flips from "does the champion survive" to
"validate the repair's constants".

### W4 ‚Äî LOGGED-mode write and read taxes (vs G-W, G-Q, G-H; SPK-H follow-up)

Measured input [SPKHQ]: dormant hook sites +2.5‚Äì3.5% deep (three sessions),
dormant routing branch +2.4/2.4/3.8% reads ‚Äî both decision rules triggered.

- **G-D** (DIRECT ‚â§ alien on every tier-0 shape): with hooks/branch present
