### 8.3 Pinless keys: the pin-window lemma

**Lemma.** For one maskId m and pins p‚ÇÅ ‚â§ p‚ÇÇ:
`fold(n, m, p‚ÇÅ) ‚âÝ fold(n, m, p‚ÇÇ)` ‚áí some tape entry has
`seq ‚àà (p‚ÇÅ, p‚ÇÇ]` with slot ‚àà m, or `retireSeq ‚àà (p‚ÇÅ, p‚ÇÇ]` for a slot
whose cone includes some atom in n's fold basis.

*Proof.* The visibility predicate `(retiredSeq‚âÝ0 ‚àß retiredSeq‚â§pin) ‚à®
(slot‚ààmask ‚àß seq‚â§pin)` is monotone in pin clause-by-clause; two pins
disagree about entry e iff e's deciding stamp (seq for the mask clause,
retiredSeq for the retired clause) lies in `(p‚ÇÅ, p‚ÇÇ]`. A mask-clause
disagreement is row 1's subject (its write bumped `slotWriteSeq[slot]`
above p‚ÇÅ, and slot ‚àà m). A retired-clause disagreement is row 2's subject
(the ring holds its retireSeq; relevance: an entry changes n's fold only
if its atom is in n's basis, and M marks n for that slot ‚Äî walks mark at
write time, propagation marks on later edge acquisition, both before any
serve that could depend on it, because serving routes through ¬ß5.2 which
consults the same columns). ‚àé

Consequence: memos need no pin in the key; rows 1‚Äì2 quoted over the window
`(min(foldPin, p), max(foldPin, p)]` decide servability in both
directions ‚Äî a memo folded *after* the pass's pin is correctly rejected
when an in-window in-mask write or relevant retirement exists (C7's
exclusion re-walked in ¬ß14). W3's keystroke storm: row 1 passes (no
k-writes), row 2 passes (urgent slot's cone disjoint ‚áí bit absent) ‚áí
memo HIT across the restart. The champion's every-retirement epoch nuke is
deleted; ring overflow and gen-stale entries fail closed to the champion's
behavior.

